After quantification of proteins content (Supplementary material, Figure 3S), the CAT content, a key enzyme in the biological defense system, was increased in both S. aureus and E. coli after exposure to C-GQDs (
                        Fig. 6

                        ). This finding underscores the impact of C-GQDs on ROS generation and the antioxidant defense mechanism within these bacterial strains. The E. coli treatment group exhibited a similar response to that of S. aureus, indicating a consistent effect of C-GQDs. Our results also revealed the ability of C-GQDs to generate H2O2 explained by elevation of SOD activity. The observed increase in SOD activity in both S. aureus and E. coli after C-GQDs treatment suggests an elevated antioxidant capacity. The SOD is pivotal in maintaining the delicate balance between oxidation and antioxidation, effectively scavenging superoxide anion free radicals. In summary, the experimental outcomes support the proposition that C-GQDs treatment stimulates ROS production in bacteria. This, in turn, indirectly triggers an elevation in SOD enzyme levels, indicating an intensified antioxidative defense response. Additionally, the observed increase in CAT activity underscores the multifaceted impact of C-GQDs on the bacterial antioxidant defense system (
                        Fig. 6
                        ). To elucidate the biocompatibility of C-GQDs and cell membrane bacteria, MDA levels were measured. MDA, the ultimate product of lipid peroxidation, serves as an indirect indicator of cellular damage. In the presented study, MDA content increased in both S. aureus and E. coli after exposure to C-GQDs suggesting an increase in lipid peroxidation and bacterial damage (Figure 4S).
